post_text:
The deadline to apply for P-EBT food benefits has
been extended to August 21. Did your child
receive free or reduced-price school meals
through the National School Lunch Program
during the 2019-2020 school year? If so, your
family may be eligible for this one-time food
benefit. Visit hhs.texas.gov/pebt to learn more
about P-EBT. For questions regarding eligibility or
if you need help applying, contact the P-EBT Call
Center at 833-613-6220. The public charge rule
does not apply to P-EBT benefits. If a family
thinks their child was incorrectly denied P-EBT
benefits, they need to contact HHS within 15 days
of receiving their denial notice by calling the PEBT Call Center or by email at
AES_PEBT_Complaints@hhsc.state.tx.us. They
must provide proof they received free to
reduced-price meals through the National School
Lunch Program, to get P-EBT benefits. Proof
includes the award letter that is sent to parents
when their children become eligible for the
National School Lunch Program. If children
attend a CEP or P2 school, a school ID or report
card can be used.

If you have a student that is new to our school district you will scroll to the bottom and select create account under the new student box. If you have any questions or trouble with registration please feel free to contact Courtney Miller or Tara Royal at 806-868-3971 or by email.

👨‍🎓 SENIOR SPOTLIGHT - SKYLER RAY 👨‍🎓
Skyler has attended Miami ISD for 4 years. During that time he has focused on his academics. He was also the team manager for football his Freshman & Sophomore years and participated in 4H Archery all 4 years of High School. Skyler plans to attend college this fall at either WTA&M or Amarillo College. Skyler enjoys video games, computer technology, archery, & hunting. He is also a very active member of Cornerstone Church & enjoys attending the camps & helping on mission trips. Skyler says "My favorite part of being a Warrior is the community of Miami and the support we receive as a student body. I am proud to be a graduate of Miami ISD and to be able to call Miami, Texas home".
🎓 Way To Go Skyler! 🎓

Skyler plans to attend college this fall at either WTA&M or Amarillo College. Skyler enjoys video games, computer technology, archery, & hunting. He is also a very active member of Cornerstone Church & enjoys attending the camps & helping on mission trips. Skyler says "My favorite part of being a Warrior is the community of Miami and the support we receive as a student body. I am proud to be a graduate of Miami ISD and to be able to call Miami, Texas home".
🎓 Way To Go Skyler! 🎓

👩‍🎓 SENIOR SPOTLIGHT - MIKA BELL 👩‍🎓
Mika has been a student at Miami School for 14 years. She has participated in Cross Country, Track, Basketball, Tennis, Cheer, FFA, 4H, & NHS during her high school years. She plans to attend West Texas A&M after graduating, but hasn't decided on her major yet. Her favorite thing about being a Warrior is how supportive the community is and how much the town of Miami likes to be involved. She says "I love the small town life. Everybody knows everybody and it's like a big family". When asked what she will remember about school, she replied "I will always remember the inside jokes in Mr. Browning's class like: What color is George Washington's white horse? Also all the memories my class has made throughout all the years of having Mrs. Ortega. I can not wait to see what the future holds for the graduate class of 2020".
🎓 Warrior Pride Through & Through, That's our Mika! 🎓

post_text: Tuesday, March 24, students need to come to school to pick up all necessary materials and supplies to begin remote learning on Wednesday. In attempt to follow social distancing, we are asking elementary students to use the elementary entrance on the north side of the building and secondary students use the south entrance by the principal's office. The building will be accessible from 8:30-4:00 on Tuesday. Please contact the school if you are not able to pick up the the materials on Tuesday so other arrangements can be made.

post_text: Due to the Governor’s executive order just announced, all schools in Texas are closed through April 3rd! Miami ISD will follow this order and will not resume face to face classes until Monday April 6th. Students will begin remote learning Wednesday, March 25-April 3.

post_text: Miami High School Prom will be on Saturday April 11, 2020. Promenade will be at 7 pm,, followed by the dinner at 7:30, & then the dance from 8-11 pm. $35.00 single or $60.00 for a couple. We have student permission forms available in the office for any student bringing a non Miami guest. These forms & the money must be paid by April 3rd in order to attend prom. Please keep in mind this could be subject to change.

Miami ISD is accepting applications for a full-time maintenance/custodial position. Applications are accessible on the school's website, www. miamiisd.net, or in the superintendent's office. Applications will be accepted until March 27 at 3:00 p.m.

Miami ISD is an equal opportunity employer . Employment at Miami ISD is based solely on a person's merit and qualifications directly related to professional competence. Miami ISD does not discriminate against any employee or applicant because of race, creed, color, religion, gender, sexual orientation, national origin, disability, age, genetic information, veteran status, marital status, pregnancy or related condition, or any other basis protected by law.

post_text: This year, Miami ISD will be having a Veterans Day program on November 11th! We are asking that pre K-12 students bring pictures of their family/friends who have served in any branch of the military. If possible, we would like pictures of them in their military uniforms. We will be showing these pictures in a PowerPoint at the program to honor our veterans! Please bring pictures to Mrs. Ortega or Mrs. Williams by Wednesday, November 6th!
